abstract.gco:CharacterString: The North America Shaded Relief data were derived from the GTOPO30 elevation data. GTOPO30 is a global digital elevation model (DEM) with a horizontal grid spacing of 30 arc seconds (approximately 1 kilometer). GTOPO30 was derived from several raster and vector sources of topographic information. It was developed between 1993 and 1996 through a collaborative effort led by staff at the U.S. Geological Survey's EROS Data Center (EDC). The following organizations participated by contributing funding or source data: the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), the United Nations Environment Programme/Global Resource Information Database (UNEP/GRID), the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID), the Instituto Nacional de Estadistica Geografica e Informatica (INEGI) of Mexico, the Geographical Survey Institute (GSI) of Japan, Manaaki Whenua Landcare Research of New Zealand, and the Scientific Committee on Antarctic Research (SCAR). This file is a replacement for the January 2003 map layer. This map layer was previously distributed as North America Shaded Relief. This layer is part of the 1997-2014 edition National Atlas of the United States.

purpose.gco:CharacterString: The Shaded Relief image was developed to portray the terrain of North America. It is intended for visual purposes only. The original GTOPO30 data must be used for conducting analysis and determining elevation values.

description.gco:CharacterString: The color shaded relief rendition was created by combining two files: 1. File one was a color elevation image, created by slicing the corrected elevation data using the ranges (listed in feet; divide by 3.2808 to get meters) and RGB color values below. This image file was converted in Adobe Photoshop from RGB to CMY (no black generated). >From To index red green blue >--------------------------------------------------- >-250 0 1 215 215 215 >1 249 2 113 153 89 >250 499 3 117 170 101 >500 999 4 149 190 113 >1000 1499 5 178 214 117 >1500 1999 6 202 226 149 >2000 2499 7 222 238 161 >2500 2999 8 242 238 161 >3000 3499 9 238 222 153 >3500 3999 10 242 206 133 >4000 4499 11 234 182 129 >4500 4999 12 218 157 121 >5000 5499 13 194 141 125 >5500 5999 14 214 157 145 >6000 6499 15 226 174 165 >6500 6999 16 222 186 182 >7000 7499 17 238 198 210 >7500 7999 18 255 206 226 >8000 8499 19 250 218 234 >8500 8999 20 255 222 230 >9000 9499 21 255 230 242 >9500 9999 22 255 242 255 >10000 19476 23 255 255 255 >Water 24 132 193 255 > 2. File two was a grayscale shaded relief rendition of the elevation data, created with the Grid HILLSHADE command using these parameters: >azimuth = 315 degrees >sun elevation = 45 degrees >Shadetype = SHADE >Vertical exaggeration = 10.0 File two was added as a black (K) band to file one (CMY), to create a CMYK color shaded relief image. Overall contrast was enhanced and excessive shading around lake boundaries was lightened, then the CMYK image was converted in Photoshop to RGB for use in the online National Atlas. The file was converted to TIFF format using the command GRIDIMAGE to create the final TIFF file, Shdrlfi020l.tif with an accompanying .tfw world file.

The mosaic of elevation data used for North America Shaded Relief was first assembled in 1999 for use on the National Atlas web site, and for a printed map at 1:10,000,000 scale published that same year. The original 1999 map layer was assembled from the following tiles of GTOPO30 elevation data: w180n90, w140n90, w100n90, w060n90, w020n90, w180n40, w140n40, w100n40, w060n40, w020n40. The tiles were ingested into Arc/INFO with the IMAGEGRID command. The resulting grids were combined into a single grid with the MERGE function. This grid was then projected into the Lambert Azimuthal Equal Area projection, centered on 100 degrees West, 45 degrees North. The .prj file used for the Arc PROJECT command contained these parameters: > INPUT > PROJECTION GEOGRAPHIC > UNITS DD > PARAMETERS > OUTPUT > PROJECTION LAMBERT_AZIMUTHAL > UNITS METERS > XSHIFT 0.0 > YSHIFT 0.0 > PARAMETERS > 0.0 > -100 0 0 > 45 0 0 > 0.0 > 0.0 > END > The western edge of the grid was extended to match that of the National Atlas of the United States Map Maker bounding rectangle, and the null cells in the extended area were converted to ocean RGB values using CON.

In 2001 and 2002, some areas of the elevation mosaic were updated with improved data provided as internal files by science staff at EROS Data Center. The first update, in October, 2001 featured two significant improvements: 1. Much of the GTOPO30 coverage of the conterminous United States was updated from higher resolution elevation data from the National Elevation Dataset; 2. Parts of northern Canada were corrected to remove a processing artifact that created an artificial pattern of "dimples" in the shaded relief. These elevation data were used for a printed National Atlas product, the 2002 "Shaded Relief of North America" map published at 1:10,000,000 scale. In the second update, in September, 2002, data for Greenland were entirely replaced by a higher resolution dataset that, however, suffered from geometric distortion. These new data for Greenland were adjusted to correct for geometric distortion in the northwest part of the island between the Robeson Channel and Cape Morris Jesup, and to improve registration with the coastline derived from World Vector Shoreline (WVS). A link coverage was created in ArcEdit containing links between the original Greenland data and the new coastline. The link coverage was used in the Arc ADJUST command to perform a linear transformation with bilinear resampling on the original image, stored as an Arc/INFO grid dataset. The resulting image is geometrically correct and fits the WVS coastline. This correction was applied to data for Greenland only.

The color shaded relief rendition was created by combining two files: 1. File one was a color elevation image, created by slicing the corrected elevation data using the ranges (listed in feet; divide by 3.2808 to get meters) and RGB color values below. This image file was converted in Adobe Photoshop from RGB to CMY (no black generated). >From To index red green blue >--------------------------------------------------- >-250 0 1 215 215 215 >1 249 2 113 153 89 >250 499 3 117 170 101 >500 999 4 149 190 113 >1000 1499 5 178 214 117 >1500 1999 6 202 226 149 >2000 2499 7 222 238 161 >2500 2999 8 242 238 161 >3000 3499 9 238 222 153 >3500 3999 10 242 206 133 >4000 4499 11 234 182 129 >4500 4999 12 218 157 121 >5000 5499 13 194 141 125 >5500 5999 14 214 157 145 >6000 6499 15 226 174 165 >6500 6999 16 222 186 182 >7000 7499 17 238 198 210 >7500 7999 18 255 206 226 >8000 8499 19 250 218 234 >8500 8999 20 255 222 230 >9000 9499 21 255 230 242 >9500 9999 22 255 242 255 >10000 19476 23 255 255 255 >Water 24 132 193 255 > 2. File two was a grayscale shaded relief rendition of the elevation data, created with the Grid HILLSHADE command using these parameters: >azimuth = 315 degrees >sun elevation = 45 degrees >Shadetype = SHADE >Vertical exaggeration = 10.0 File two was added as a black (K) band to file one (CMY), to create a CMYK color shaded relief image. Overall contrast was enhanced and excessive shading around lake boundaries was lightened, then the CMYK image was converted in Photoshop to RGB for use in the online National Atlas. This image contains color shaded relief in RGB color space. For access to its sliced elevation and grayscale shaded relief components, or to the original 16-bit DEM data (Elevation2002), please contact the National Atlas. These same elevation data were also used for a printed National Atlas product, the 2002 "Shaded Relief of North America" map published at 1:10,000,000 scale. Updated source data and intermediate products, as well as the final color shaded relief image (in CMYK) used on the printed map, are also available from the National Atlas.
